ve indicators like mentions of anarchists in news reports and by\nactivists adopting anarchist modes of organization, tactics, and social goals-\nwhether or not they claim that label. The authors of this Element argue that\nthe very crises that generated radical mobilizations since the turn of the\nmillennium have both led activists to reject other strategies for social\ntransformation and to see anarchist practices as appropriate to the challenges\nof our time. This turn is clearly apparent in the Americas and Europe, and has\nreverberations on an even broader transnational, perhaps global, scale. This\nsuggests the need for research on social movements to consider anarchists and\nother marginalized radical traditions more fully, not just as objects of\nstudy, but as important sources of theory.\n\nElement\n\n  * Element\n  * Metrics\n\nElement contents\n\n  * Summary\n  * References\n\nGet access\n\n  * Copy\n\n  * Share\n\n  * Share\n\n  * Share\n\n  * Share\n\n  * Post\n\n  * Share\n\n  * Mail\n\n  * Share\n\n## Keywords\n\nanarchismsocial movementsrevolutiondemocracyglobalization\n\nType\n\n    Element\n\nInformation\n\n    \n\nSeries: Elements in Contentious Politics\n\nDOI: https://doi.org/10.1017/9781009495219 [Opens in a new window]\n\nOnline ISBN: 9781009495219\n\nPublisher: Cambridge University Press\n\nPrint publication: 11 April 2024\n\n## Access options\n\nGet access to the full version of this content by using one of the access\noptions below. (Log in options will check for institutional or personal\naccess. Content may require purchase if you do not have access.)\n\n### Check access\n\n#### Institutional login\n\nWe recognised you are associated with one or more institutions that don't have\naccess to this content. If you should have access, please contact your\nlibrarian. Access through your institution\n\nChange institution\n\n#### Personal login\n\nLog in with your Cambridge Core account or society details. Log in\n\n### Element purchase\n\n#### D